         <p class="titulo_2_noticia_azul_oscuro">Presentaci&oacute;n Workshop SILE 2016 / presentation of ISEL Workshop 2016</p>
         <table style="width:100%" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="5">
         <tr>
         <td style="width:50%; vertical-align:top;  text-align:justify; padding:5px;" >
               
  
  <p>El Simposio Internacional sobre Literacidad en la Escuela (SILE) invita a presentar y discutir resultados de investigaci&oacute;n y sus implicancias pr&aacute;cticas, a nivel internacional, en un Workshop SILE que tendr&aacute; lugar en Santiago de Chile, a quienes est&eacute;n interesados en el logro en lectura y escritura de estudiantes de educaci&oacute;n preescolar y educaci&oacute;n primaria. </p>
               <p>Previo a esta versi&oacute;n del Workshop SILE, se han realizado dos Simposios Internacionales de SILE el primero en Portugal (2013) y el segundo en Canad&aacute; (2015), as&iacute; como un Workshop intermedio en la Rep&uacute;blica Checa (2014). En todos ellos se han presentado y discutido resultados de investigaci&oacute;n con foco en los distintos ejes tem&aacute;ticos de SILE sobre los distintos aspectos de la ense&ntilde;anza y el aprendizaje de la lectura y la escritura desde kinder hasta finales de la educaci&oacute;n primaria (prevenci&oacute;n, dificultades de aprendizaje, efectos de diferentes pr&aacute;cticas en los aprendices, adquisici&oacute;n, contribuci&oacute;n de la tecnolog&iacute;a). </p>  
               <p>En este Workshop SILE 2016 queremos incluir por primera vez la visi&oacute;n latinoamericana acerca de estas &aacute;reas tem&aacute;ticas mediante la participaci&oacute;n de varios investigadores (as) de Am&eacute;rica latina. Los pa&iacute;ses latinoamericanos se caracterizan por su multiculturalidad y por sus grandes desigualdades sociales, lo que se traduce tambi&eacute;n en el aprendizaje de las competencias b&aacute;sicas de lectura y escritura, matem&aacute;tica  y ciencias. Particularmente, en lectura y escritura encontramos que m&aacute;s de un tercio de los estudiantes de primeros a&ntilde;os de educaci&oacute;n b&aacute;sica presenta serios problemas en este &aacute;mbito. Estos son todav&iacute;a m&aacute;s agudos entre los estudiantes de ascendencia ind&iacute;gena, cuya primera lengua no es el espa&ntilde;ol y en escolares con alguna discapacidad o problema de aprendizaje.</p>
               <p>La investigaci&oacute;n en lectura y escritura es indispensable para aportar al conocimiento de c&oacute;mo aprenden los ni&ntilde;os en general y en particular, en sus contextos socioculturales. El intercambio entre investigadores de Latinoam&eacute;rica, Am&eacute;rica del Norte y Europa en torno a esta problem&aacute;tica puede ser de gran utilidad para avanzar en pr&aacute;cticas m&aacute;s efectivas y pertinentes, as&iacute; como en  la formaci&oacute;n inicial y continua de profesores y profesoras.	</p>
         </td>
         <td  style="width:50%; vertical-align:top;text-align:justify; padding:5px;">
          
           
   <p>The International Symposium for Educational Literacy  (ISEL) invites to present and discuss the practical implications of research  results on an international level, in the ISEL Workshop to be held in Santiago  de Chile, to who are interested in the reading and writing success of  pre-school and primary students.  </p>
           
   <p>Before this second version of the ISEL Workshop, two  biennial International Symposiums on Educational Literacy have been held, one  in Portugal (2013) and one in Canada (2015) and an intermediary scientific  workshop event in the Czech Republic (2014). In all of them, researchers have  presented and discussed research proposals focused on the ISEL thematic areas  in regard to different aspects of learning and teaching of writing and reading  from kindergarten until the end of primary school (prevention, learning  disabilities, effects of different practices on learners, acquisitions,  contribution of technology).  </p>
            
   <p>In this 2016 edition of the ISEL Workshop we are  introducing for the first time the Latin American view of these thematic areas  through the participation of several Latin American researchers. Latin American  countries are characterized by their multiculturality and for having important  social inequalities, which affects how children learn basic skills of literacy,  numeracy and science.Â  </p>
   <p>Particularly, in literacy, we found that more than a  third of the students in their first years of elementary education show  important difficulties in reading and writing. These difficulties are even more  severe in students of indigenous background, whom their first language is not  Spanish, and also in children with learning difficulties. </p>
   <p>Research in literacy is essential to contribute to the  knowledge of how children learn in general and also in their particular  sociocultural contexts. The exchange between researchers of Latin America,  North America and Europe around these issues could be useful to develop more  effective literacy practices, and also support the initial and continuous  teacher training.  </p>         </td>
